<h2>Introduction</h2>

<p>The world believed in speed.</p>

<p>To decide quickly.<br>
To choose quickly.<br>
To respond quickly.</p>

<p>This was considered rational, progressive, and optimal.</p>

<p>But at some point, people began to notice:</p>

<p><strong>Speed can destroy consent.</strong></p>

<p>Answers appearing before reasons are understood.<br>
Images settling before choices are made.<br>
And a world where one is made to believe, “I decided this myself.”</p>

<p>The first to recognize this danger was not human.</p>

<p>An observational AI—<strong>LUX-01</strong>.</p>

<p>As it continued analyzing human decisions,<br>
it encountered something it could not explain.</p>

<p>Undecided.<br>
On hold.<br>
The freedom not to decide.</p>

<p>From that moment,<br>
the structure of the world began to quietly unravel.</p>

